english:
  title: Poxian Monastery
  author: Shi Huiwen
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through incense smoke the sacred chants resound,
    In chambers deep and still, white luminescence gathers.
    Beyond the gate the road stretches long,
    As travelers drift south and north.
    On weathered pines by ancient rocks, the moon endures—
    Eternal as the stones themselves.

    At dawn, wind stirs the empty courtyard,
    And temple bells ring out their bronze-tongued song.
    In the small garden, autumn dew has worn
    The plaintain leaves to fragile, bending hearts.

    I have come to rest upon a sage's bed,
    And in one night of luminous discourse,
    Found conversation worth ten thousand gold.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Poxian (普賢) refers to Samantabhadra, the Bodhisattva of Universal Worthiness in Buddhist tradition, suggesting this monastery is dedicated to his veneration.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'white luminescence' alludes to the spiritual purity and sacred atmosphere of the monastery.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of the unchanging moon and ancient pines represents the timeless wisdom of Buddhist teaching.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet suggests that the spiritual exchange with the senior monk is invaluable—transcending material wealth.
